For the next question, join the panels_total data to the comics data and compute the day of the week of the comic. Set label = TRUE to see the weekday names. Summarize the data to determine the average number of panels for each day of the week. You should see that most days are indistinguishable, except for Sunday, which is much longer.

# Question 05
panels_total |>
  inner_join(comics, by = "image_path") |>
  mutate(wday = wday(date, label = TRUE)) |>
  group_by(wday) |>
  summarize(n = mean(n))

Research Question: Last Panel Captions

In this last section, we will try to look at one of the research questions we have about this data. Usually, the punchline of a comic comes in the last panel. This can be a verbal punchline, but can also be a punchline described through the visual message. Weâ€™d like to understand when and how often the final panel contains a caption in order to understand how often each type of punchline gets used. Letâ€™s try to do this with the techniques weâ€™ve learned so far!

To start, two hints to speed things along. First, notice that the following code (the fairly rare grouped filter) gives us all of the final panels in the data:

panels |>
  group_by(image_path) |>
  filter(panel_id == max(panel_id)) |>
  ungroup()

Secondly, the following summary function, when put into a pipe with all of the variable, will tell us the proportion of final panels that contain some caption in them. This is a bit complicated because we need to ignore â€œcaptionsâ€ at the bottom of the final panel, because this is often where the date or creatorâ€™s signature appears.

  summarize(
    last_caption = 100 * as.numeric(any((xmid >= xmin & xmid <= xmax) &
                                        (ymid >= (ymin * 0.3 + ymax * 0.7) &
                                        ymid <= ymax))))

For the next question, put together the two hints above to create a dataset with one row for each comic with a column last_caption equal to 0 if the comic does not have a caption in the final panel and 100 if it does.

# Question 08
panels |>
  group_by(image_path) |>
  filter(panel_id == max(panel_id)) |>
  ungroup() |>
  inner_join(captions, by = "image_path") |>
  group_by(image_path) |>
  summarize(
    last_caption = 100 * as.numeric(any((xmid >= xmin & xmid <= xmax) &
                                        (ymid >= (ymin * 0.3 + ymax * 0.7) &
                                        ymid <= ymax))))

Now, in the next block, modify your code from before to group the data by the panel_id and compute the average proportion of comics that have a caption in the final panel based on the total number of panels. Create a plot to visualize the relationship.

# Question 09
panels |>
  group_by(image_path) |>
  filter(panel_id == max(panel_id)) |>
  ungroup() |>
  inner_join(captions, by = "image_path") |>
  group_by(panel_id, image_path) |>
  summarize(
    last_caption = 100 * as.numeric(any((xmid >= xmin & xmid <= xmax) &
                                        (ymid >= (ymin * 0.3 + ymax * 0.7) &
                                         ymid <= ymax)))) |>
  summarize(mu = mean(last_caption)) |>
  ggplot(aes(panel_id, mu)) +
    geom_point() +
    labs(x = "Total Number of Panels",
         y = "Percentage with Caption in Final Panel")

Finally, compute the proportion of comics with with a caption in the final panel as a function of the year of the comic.

# Question 10
panels |>
  group_by(image_path) |>
  filter(panel_id == max(panel_id)) |>
  ungroup() |>
  inner_join(captions, by = "image_path") |>
  group_by(image_path) |>
  summarize(
    last_caption = 100 * as.numeric(any((xmid >= xmin & xmid <= xmax) &
                                        (ymid >= (ymin * 0.3 + ymax * 0.7) &
                                        ymid <= ymax)))) |>
  inner_join(comics, by = "image_path") |>
  mutate(year = year(date)) |>
  group_by(year) |>
  summarize(mu = mean(last_caption)) |>
  ggplot(aes(year, mu)) +
    geom_point() +
    labs(x = "Year",
         y = "Percentage of Comics with Caption in Final Panel")
